1 (25) To establish a subcommittee of the school board or committee to decrease obesity and
2 address school health and wellness policies for students and employees consistent with § 16-21-28.
3 (26) To annually undertake a minimum of six (6) hours of professional development as set
4 forth and described in § 16-2-5.1.
5 (27) To establish policies governing the implementation of the incorporation of career and
6 technical education programs into the kindergarten through grade twelve (K-12) curricula that
7 include knowledge of careers and all types of employment opportunities, including, but not limited
8 to, registered apprenticeships in accordance with chapter 45 of title 28, and emphasizing the
9 advantages of completing school with marketable skills.
10 (b) Nothing in this section shall be deemed to limit or interfere with the rights of teachers
11 and other school employees to collectively bargain pursuant to chapters 9.3 and 9.4 of title 28 or to
12 allow any school committee to abrogate any agreement reached by collective bargaining.
13 (c) The elected school committees of each city, town, or regional school district, or the
14 chief executive officer of any municipality having an appointed school committee, shall have the
15 power to bind their successors and successor committees by entering into contracts of employment
16 in the exercise of their governmental functions.
17 (d) Notwithstanding any provisions of the general laws to the contrary, the requirement
18 defined in subsections (d) through (f) of this section shall apply. The school committee of each
19 school district shall be responsible for maintaining a school budget that does not result in a debt.
20 (e) The school committee shall, within thirty (30) days after the close of the first and second
21 quarters of the state’s fiscal year, adopt a budget as may be necessary to enable it to operate without
22 incurring a debt, as described in subsection (d).
23 (f) In the event that any obligation, encumbrance, or expenditure by a superintendent of
24 schools or a school committee is in excess of the amount budgeted or that any revenue is less than
25 the amount budgeted, the school committee shall within five (5) working days of its discovery of
26 potential or actual over expenditure or revenue deficiency submit a written statement of the amount
27 of and cause for the over obligation or over expenditure or revenue deficiency to the city or town
28 council president and any other person who by local charter or statute serves as the city or town’s
29 executive officer; the statement shall further include a statement of the school committee’s plan for
30 corrective actions necessary to meet the requirements of subsection (d). The plan shall be approved
31 by the auditor general and also submitted to the division of municipal finance.
32 (g) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, whether of general or specific application,
33 and notwithstanding any contrary provision of any city or town charter or ordinance, the elected
34 school committee of any city, town, and regional school district shall be, and is hereby authorized
